         <abstract>
            <p>Given any data points $x_1,\ldots, x_n$ in $\mathbf{R}^s$ and values $f(x_1),\ldots, f(x_n)$ of a function $f$, Shepard's global interpolation formula reads as follows: $$S^0_pf(x) = \sum_i f(x_i)w_i(x),\quad w_i(x) = |x - x_i|^{-p}/\sum_j |x - x_j|^{-p},$$ where $|\cdot|$ denotes the Euclidean norm in $\mathbf{R}^s$. This interpolation scheme is stable, but if $p &gt; 1$, the gradient of the interpolating function vanishes in all data points. The interpolation operator $S^q_p$ is defined by replacing the values $f(x_i)$ in $S^0_pf$ by Taylor polynomials of $f$ of degree $q \in \mathbf{N}$. In this paper, we investigate the approximating power of $S^q_p$ for all values of $p, q$ and $s$.</p>
          </abstract>
